ted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aToo often, history and knowledge of Indigenous-settler conflict over land take the form of confidential reports prepared for court challenges. To Share, Not Surrender offers an entirely new approach, opening scholarship to the public and augmenting it with First Nations community expertise. The authors take us back to when James Douglas and his family relocated to Fort Victoria on Vancouver Island in 1849, critically tracing the transition from treaty-making in the colony of Vancouver Island to reserve formation in the colony of British Columbia. Informed by the spirit of cel’aṉ’en – “our culture, the way of our people” – this multivocal work includes essays, translations/interpretations of the treaties into the SENĆOŦEN and Lekwungen languages, and contributions by participants of the Songhees, Huu-ay-aht, and WSANEC peoples. As an all-embracing exploration of the struggle over land, To Share, Not Surrender advances the urgent task of reconciliation in Canada.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aIndigenous peoplesxLand tenurezBritish ColumbiaxHistory. 0aIndigenous peoplesxLegal status, laws, etczBritish ColumbiaxHistory. 0aIndigenous peoplesxLegal status, laws, etc.zBritish ColumbiaxHistory. 0aIndigenous peopleszBritish ColumbiaxGovernment relationsxHistory. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Indigenous Studies.2bisacsh1 aBrazier, Graham, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrazier, Graham, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aCarlson, Keith Thor, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aClifford, Robert, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCook, Peter, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/